	author       = {Butchart, Stuart H. M. and Clarke, Martin and Smith, Robert J. and Sykes, Rachel E. and Scharlemann, Jörn P. W. and Harfoot, Mike and Buchanan, Graeme M. and Angulo, Ariadne and Balmford, Andrew and Bertzky, Bastian and Brooks, Thomas M. and Carpenter, Kent E. and Comeros‐Raynal, Mia T. and Cornell, John and Ficetola, G. Francesco and Fishpool, Lincoln D. C. and Fuller, Richard A. and Geldmann, Jonas and Harwell, Heather and Hilton‐Taylor, Craig and Hoffmann, Michael and Joolia, Ackbar and Joppa, Lucas and Kingston, Naomi and May, Ian and Milam, Amy and Polidoro, Beth and Ralph, Gina and Richman, Nadia and Rondinini, Carlo and Segan, Daniel B. and Skolnik, Benjamin and Spalding, Mark D. and Stuart, Simon N. and Symes, Andy and Taylor, Joseph and Visconti, Piero and Watson, James E. M. and Wood, Louisa and Burgess, Neil D.},
	year         = 2015,
	journal      = {Conservation Letters},
	volume       = 8,
	number       = 5,
	pages        = {329--337},
	doi          = {10.1111/conl.12158},
	issn         = {1755-263X},
	url          = {https://conbio.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/conl.12158},
	urldate      = {2020-02-21},
	abstract     = {Governments have committed to conserving ≥17\% of terrestrial and ≥10\% of marine environments globally, especially “areas of particular importance for biodiversity” through “ecologically representative” Protected Area (PA) systems or other “area-based conservation measures”, while individual countries have committed to conserve 3–50\% of their land area. We estimate that PAs currently cover 14.6\% of terrestrial and 2.8\% of marine extent, but 59–68\% of ecoregions, 77–78\% of important sites for biodiversity, and 57\% of 25,380 species have inadequate coverage. The existing 19.7 million km2 terrestrial PA network needs only 3.3 million km2 to be added to achieve 17\% terrestrial coverage. However, it would require nearly doubling to achieve, cost-efficiently, coverage targets for all countries, ecoregions, important sites, and species. Poorer countries have the largest relative shortfalls. Such extensive and rapid expansion of formal PAs is unlikely to be achievable. Greater focus is therefore needed on alternative approaches, including community- and privately managed sites and other effective area-based conservation measures.},
